rful pressure groups in the period and the 1972 Thalidomide campaign and its effect on the Heath government. Given the recent emergence of the history of disability in Britain as a major area of research, the book will be ideal for academics, students and activists seeking a better understanding of the topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPeople with disabilitiesxGovernment policyxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxServices forxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPublic welfarexHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831111964350 cprintz978144731642840uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447316435?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447316435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447316435/original  a978-3-11-119643-5  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles